673
00:31:24,542 --> 00:31:26,125
<i>because one of
the chief lawyers</i>

674
00:31:26,209 --> 00:31:27,751
<i>in the
counterterrorism division</i>

675
00:31:27,834 --> 00:31:30,751
happened to be married
to another CIA employee

676
00:31:30,834 --> 00:31:31,876
who was in something called

677
00:31:31,959 --> 00:31:34,292
the Office
of Technical Services.

678
00:31:34,375 --> 00:31:35,959
<i>This involved psychologists.</i>

679
00:31:36,042 --> 00:31:38,167
<i>And there was
a psychologist on contract,</i>

680
00:31:38,250 --> 00:31:42,083
<i>Jim Mitchell,
who had written
a report for the CIA.</i>

681
00:31:42,167 --> 00:31:44,042
<i>This report was based
on what was believed</i>

682
00:31:44,125 --> 00:31:45,417
<i>to be an Al-Qaeda manual,</i>

683
00:31:45,500 --> 00:31:48,083
<i>and it included details
on interrogations.</i>

684
00:31:48,167 --> 00:31:51,083
Gibney:<i> The manual was called</i>
<i>"The Manchester Manual"</i>

685
00:31:51,167 --> 00:31:54,417
<i>in honor of where it was found
in Manchester, England,</i>

686
00:31:54,500 --> 00:31:55,792
<i>by Ali Soufan.</i>

687
00:31:55,876 --> 00:31:58,250
Soufan:<i> I was</i>
<i>in Manchester investigating</i>

688
00:31:58,334 --> 00:32:00,000
<i>a member of Al-Qaeda.</i>

689
00:32:00,083 --> 00:32:02,876
<i>And we did
a search of his house</i>

690
00:32:02,959 --> 00:32:04,709
<i>where we found
a handwritten book,</i>

691
00:32:04,792 --> 00:32:07,500
<i>"The Manchester Manual."</i>

692
00:32:07,584 --> 00:32:10,375
<i>It's mostly
about urban warfare.</i>

693
00:32:10,459 --> 00:32:13,751
And it has a section about
what happens if you get caught.

694
00:32:13,834 --> 00:32:17,626
<i>What should you
expect to endure?</i>

695
00:32:17,709 --> 00:32:20,375
<i>It talks about
very harsh techniques,</i>

696
00:32:20,459 --> 00:32:23,626
<i>beatings, rape,
they're going to be sodomized,</i>

697
00:32:23,709 --> 00:32:26,083
<i>their family going
to be tortured.</i>

698
00:32:26,167 --> 00:32:28,584
These are the things
that were ingrained

699
00:32:28,667 --> 00:32:31,375
in the head
of Qaeda operatives.

700
00:32:32,709 --> 00:32:34,667
Gibney:
<i>Soufan recognized it</i>
<i>as a kind of</i>

701
00:32:34,751 --> 00:32:36,709
<i>cut-and-paste
terrorist pamphlet.</i>

702
00:32:36,792 --> 00:32:39,083
<i>But the CIA imagined
it might be</i>

703
00:32:39,167 --> 00:32:41,000
<i>a window into
the Islamist mind.</i>

704
00:32:41,083 --> 00:32:44,125
<i>So they hired a psychologist
named James Mitchell</i>

705
00:32:44,209 --> 00:32:45,459
<i>to analyze it.</i>

706
00:32:45,542 --> 00:32:47,292
<i>He and his colleague,
Bruce Jessen,</i>

707
00:32:47,375 --> 00:32:50,584
<i>concluded that the manual
was a diabolical guide</i>

708
00:32:50,667 --> 00:32:52,834
<i>to play mind games
on interrogators,</i>

709
00:32:52,918 --> 00:32:55,542
<i>which could only be overcome
through harsh physical</i>

710
00:32:55,626 --> 00:32:58,459
<i>and psychological
countermeasures.</i>

711
00:32:58,542 --> 00:33:00,375
<i>Even though those
techniques were milder</i>

712
00:33:00,459 --> 00:33:02,709
<i>than the torture
expected by the manual,</i>

713
00:33:02,792 --> 00:33:05,125
<i>the message found favor
at the agency.</i>

714
00:33:05,209 --> 00:33:07,209
<i>Mitchell, who had
no experience</i>

715
00:33:07,292 --> 00:33:08,626
<i>interrogating anyone,</i>

716
00:33:08,709 --> 00:33:10,751
<i>was the only candidate
considered</i>

717
00:33:10,834 --> 00:33:12,250
<i>for the job of inventing</i>

718
00:33:12,334 --> 00:33:16,000
<i>the CIA's new system
of interrogation.</i>

719
00:33:16,083 --> 00:33:17,792
Jones:<i> There was</i>
<i>no blue ribbon commission.</i>

720
00:33:17,876 --> 00:33:20,000
There was no outreach
to the FBI

721
00:33:20,083 --> 00:33:22,000
or to the Department
of Defense

722
00:33:22,083 --> 00:33:24,042
or any other US agency,

723
00:33:24,125 --> 00:33:26,292
or foreign entity,
for that matter.

724
00:33:26,375 --> 00:33:28,125
Gibney:
<i>The CIA's hiring policy</i>

725
00:33:28,209 --> 00:33:29,209
<i>was much more casual.</i>

726
00:33:29,292 --> 00:33:31,417
<i>A CTC lawyer whose pictures</i>

727
00:33:31,500 --> 00:33:33,167
<i>have been scrubbed
from the internet</i>

728
00:33:33,250 --> 00:33:35,334
<i>just asked his wife
if she knew anyone</i>

729
00:33:35,417 --> 00:33:36,834
<i>who might be good
for the job.</i>

730
00:33:36,918 --> 00:33:39,584
Jones:<i> This lawyer says,</i>
<i>"Abu Zubaydah's been captured.</i>

731
00:33:39,667 --> 00:33:41,167
<i>I don't know what we're going
to do with this guy."</i>

732
00:33:41,250 --> 00:33:43,626
And she says, "Well,
I got a guy in my office

733
00:33:43,709 --> 00:33:45,250
"who just wrote a report

734
00:33:45,334 --> 00:33:47,834
"on this believed-to-be
an Al-Qaeda training manual.

735
00:33:47,918 --> 00:33:49,209
You should talk to him."

736
00:33:54,959 --> 00:33:57,751
Mitchell:<i> I got</i>
<i>a phone call from the CIA</i>

737
00:33:57,834 --> 00:34:00,918
<i>and they said, "You need
to come in tomorrow."</i>

738
00:34:01,000 --> 00:34:02,918
I was curious
because that was,

739
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:06,459
you know, that sounds like
comic book, uh, material.

740
00:34:06,542 --> 00:34:07,751
So I went.

741
00:34:10,292 --> 00:34:12,375
<i>I parked in the furthest space
in the parking lot,</i>

742
00:34:12,459 --> 00:34:14,125
<i>the only place
I could find.</i>

743
00:34:14,209 --> 00:34:18,876
<i>That building is a labyrinth
of hallways and rooms.</i>

744
00:34:18,959 --> 00:34:19,959
<i>I got to the door,</i>

745
00:34:20,042 --> 00:34:22,125
<i>and they rushed me
into the room,</i>

746
00:34:22,209 --> 00:34:24,792
told me that they had
captured Abu Zubaydah,

747
00:34:24,876 --> 00:34:27,209
and asked me
if I would deploy

748
00:34:27,292 --> 00:34:29,667
with the interrogation team

749
00:34:29,751 --> 00:34:33,375
to help them... recognize

750
00:34:33,459 --> 00:34:36,042
if he was using
sophisticated resistance

751
00:34:36,125 --> 00:34:37,334
to interrogation techniques

752
00:34:37,417 --> 00:34:39,250
to resist
providing information.

753
00:34:39,334 --> 00:34:42,375
Lawyer: He said he provided
psychological support.

754
00:34:42,459 --> 00:34:43,626
What does that mean?

755
00:34:43,709 --> 00:34:46,375
He provided, uh, research

756
00:34:46,459 --> 00:34:49,375
and applied
psychological support,

757
00:34:49,459 --> 00:34:51,876
-uh, to the agency.
-Lawyer: Mm-hmm.

758
00:34:51,959 --> 00:34:53,500
Um, so he did research?

759
00:34:53,584 --> 00:34:55,125
I assume so.

760
00:34:55,209 --> 00:34:56,751
Lawyer:
You don't know?

761
00:34:57,500 --> 00:34:58,584
No.

762
00:34:58,667 --> 00:35:00,459
Jones:<i> So Jim Mitchell</i>
<i>walks in the door,</i>

763
00:35:00,542 --> 00:35:03,667
says that I have experience
in interrogations,

764
00:35:03,751 --> 00:35:05,709
<i>describes what he would do,</i>

765
00:35:05,792 --> 00:35:07,959
<i>and Jose Rodriguez says,
"You're hired,</i>

766
00:35:08,042 --> 00:35:09,751
"and we're going
to put you on a flight

767
00:35:09,834 --> 00:35:12,626
to the first detention site
right now."

768
00:35:13,918 --> 00:35:14,959
No other vetting.

769
00:35:15,042 --> 00:35:19,834
(airplane whooshing)

770
00:35:24,626 --> 00:35:28,167
(insects chirping)

771
00:35:28,250 --> 00:35:31,209
Gaudin:
<i>Those first few days</i>
<i>were very chaotic.</i>

772
00:35:31,292 --> 00:35:32,918
<i>He was very wounded</i>

773
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:35,167
and sometimes while we
were talking to him,

774
00:35:35,250 --> 00:35:37,042
the doctors had to come in
and change bandages,

775
00:35:37,125 --> 00:35:38,417
or change dressings.

776
00:35:38,500 --> 00:35:40,584
And sometimes, the,
the medical folks would say,

777
00:35:40,667 --> 00:35:43,667
"You can't talk to him
for a little while.
We need to let him rest."

778
00:35:44,834 --> 00:35:46,834
Soufan:
<i>They said he was dehydrated.</i>

779
00:35:46,918 --> 00:35:49,500
<i>So Stephen and I
were caring for him.</i>

780
00:35:49,584 --> 00:35:52,000
<i>We put ice on his lips.</i>

781
00:35:52,083 --> 00:35:54,792
Ali is holding his hand.
Ali's rubbing his forehead.

782
00:35:54,876 --> 00:35:57,500
Ali's praying with him,
saying, "Hang in there, brother.

783
00:35:57,584 --> 00:35:59,709
"Don't worry. We're going
to take care of you.

784
00:35:59,792 --> 00:36:01,250
You're going to be okay."

785
00:36:01,334 --> 00:36:03,292
He defecates
all over himself.

786
00:36:04,959 --> 00:36:06,500
Soufan:
<i>Later on, I don't know,</i>

787
00:36:06,584 --> 00:36:09,292
<i>two or three o'clock
in the morning,
the medic came in</i>

788
00:36:09,375 --> 00:36:11,876
and he said,
"Is this guy important?"

789
00:36:11,959 --> 00:36:13,918
And I said,
"Yeah, I believe so."

790
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:15,667
He said,
"Well, if, you know,

791
00:36:15,751 --> 00:36:18,542
"if you think
he knows information,

792
00:36:18,626 --> 00:36:19,876
"you better get it
from him now.

793
00:36:19,959 --> 00:36:21,417
You better go
and talk to him now."

794
00:36:21,500 --> 00:36:23,751
I said, "Why?"
He said, "Because he's septic.

795
00:36:23,834 --> 00:36:25,959
"I don't think he will live

796
00:36:26,042 --> 00:36:28,125
to see the morning."

797
00:36:28,209 --> 00:36:31,709
<i>So the chief of base wrote
a cable about the situation,</i>

798
00:36:31,792 --> 00:36:34,834
<i>and the answer came back,
short and sweet:</i>

799
00:36:34,918 --> 00:36:37,542
"Death is not an option."

800
00:36:37,626 --> 00:36:40,792
<i>We had to come up
with a cover story</i>

801
00:36:40,876 --> 00:36:43,584
<i>to take him to a hospital.</i>

802
00:36:43,667 --> 00:36:46,125
<i>We were wearing
military uniforms,</i>

803
00:36:46,209 --> 00:36:48,125
<i>said he was one
of our soldiers,</i>

804
00:36:48,209 --> 00:36:50,459
<i>that he went crazy
and he got shot.</i>

805
00:36:50,542 --> 00:36:53,792
<i>And that's why we're
taking him for medical care.</i>

806
00:36:53,876 --> 00:36:55,042
Reporter:
<i>Abu Zubaydah,</i>

807
00:36:55,125 --> 00:36:56,626
<i>Al-Qaeda's
top field commander,</i>

808
00:36:56,709 --> 00:36:57,751
<i>is talking.</i>

809
00:36:57,834 --> 00:36:59,417
<i>The trouble is,
American interrogators</i>

810
00:36:59,500 --> 00:37:01,626
<i>are not sure
whether to believe him.</i>

811
00:37:01,709 --> 00:37:03,042
Donald Rumsfeld:
<i>I don't know</i>
<i>that I want to give</i>

812
00:37:03,125 --> 00:37:05,918
<i>a day-to-day report
on, on his, uh,</i>

813
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:09,792
<i>how enthusiastic he is
about his situation.</i>

814
00:37:09,876 --> 00:37:14,042
<i>Um... he is not well.</i>

815
00:37:14,125 --> 00:37:16,417
<i>He's got
several bullet holes in him,</i>

816
00:37:16,500 --> 00:37:17,918
<i>and, uh...</i>

817
00:37:19,334 --> 00:37:20,751
<i>well, how fast he'll recover</i>

818
00:37:20,834 --> 00:37:24,584
<i>and when he'll start
cooperating, time will tell.</i>

819
00:37:28,167 --> 00:37:30,334
Jones:<i> While Abu Zubaydah</i>
<i>is in the hospital,</i>

820
00:37:30,417 --> 00:37:31,959
<i>things begin to change.</i>

821
00:37:33,209 --> 00:37:34,959
<i>It's during
this period of time</i>

822
00:37:35,042 --> 00:37:37,918
<i>that Jim Mitchell is sent
to the detention site.</i>

823
00:37:39,042 --> 00:37:40,834
<i>He goes merely
as an observer</i>

824
00:37:40,918 --> 00:37:43,876
<i>and to provide feedback
to CIA headquarters.</i>

825
00:37:43,959 --> 00:37:46,209
<i>But his influence
becomes very clear.</i>

826
00:37:46,292 --> 00:37:48,000
<i>They talk about
returning Abu Zubaydah</i>

827
00:37:48,083 --> 00:37:50,167
<i>to the detention site
in an all-white room,</i>

828
00:37:50,250 --> 00:37:51,375
<i>which is very bright,</i>

829
00:37:51,459 --> 00:37:53,792
<i>kept cold.</i>

830
00:37:53,876 --> 00:37:56,792
<i>He'll be kept naked
and sleep deprived.</i>

831
00:37:56,876 --> 00:37:58,834
<i>These are the ideas
that are coming about.</i>

832
00:37:58,918 --> 00:38:00,792
Even though he's not
particularly doing
the interrogation,

833
00:38:00,876 --> 00:38:02,751
these are his ideas
that he's pushing forward.

834
00:38:02,834 --> 00:38:04,626
Gibney: They weren't
asking you at that time

835
00:38:04,709 --> 00:38:06,626
to help with interrogations,
or were they?

836
00:38:06,709 --> 00:38:08,459
Not to do
interrogations.

837
00:38:08,542 --> 00:38:11,125
They were help-- asking me
to help brainstorm

838
00:38:11,209 --> 00:38:14,500
with the interrogation team,
the whole interrogation team,

839
00:38:14,584 --> 00:38:17,626
uh, any countermeasures
that they might use,

840
00:38:17,709 --> 00:38:21,667
if he was employing
resistance techniques.

841
00:38:23,459 --> 00:38:26,209
Soufan:<i> He stayed</i>
<i>in the hospital, recovering.</i>

842
00:38:26,292 --> 00:38:29,000
We get a clearance
from the doctors
that we can talk to him,

843
00:38:29,083 --> 00:38:32,125
<i>and we went back
to talking about</i>

844
00:38:32,209 --> 00:38:33,751
<i>what he knows
about a plot.</i>

845
00:38:35,375 --> 00:38:37,000
<i>So I asked him,</i>

846
00:38:37,083 --> 00:38:40,709
<i>"Do you know if Bin Laden
is planning to do anything?"</i>

847
00:38:40,792 --> 00:38:42,542
He said, "Yes,
Al-Qaeda is planning

848
00:38:42,626 --> 00:38:43,918
"to do something.

849
00:38:44,000 --> 00:38:45,417
He has his own people."

850
00:38:45,500 --> 00:38:48,292
I said, "Are you aware of
an operation that's ongoing?"

851
00:38:48,375 --> 00:38:50,709
He said, "Yes,
there's an operation

852
00:38:50,792 --> 00:38:54,500
<i>against an American facility
in a foreign country."</i>

853
00:38:54,584 --> 00:38:56,542
So I said,
"Who's doing this operation?

854
00:38:56,626 --> 00:38:57,918
He said, "al-Zayyat."

855
00:38:58,000 --> 00:39:00,042
We know al-Zayyat
is an alias

856
00:39:00,125 --> 00:39:02,250
<i>for Abu Mohamed al-Masri,</i>

857
00:39:02,334 --> 00:39:03,542
<i>who was the mastermind</i>

858
00:39:03,626 --> 00:39:06,751
<i>of the East Africa
embassy bombings.</i>

859
00:39:06,834 --> 00:39:09,083
Gaudin:<i> So Ali and I</i>
<i>came up with a plan</i>

860
00:39:09,167 --> 00:39:11,250
<i>to show him a photo
of this guy,</i>

861
00:39:11,334 --> 00:39:14,417
and if he identifies him,
he's working with us.

862
00:39:14,500 --> 00:39:17,918
I'm not saying he's giving us
the keys to the kingdom,

863
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:19,834
but we can walk out
of the room and go,

864
00:39:19,918 --> 00:39:21,250
"Hey, I think we're
at the point now we can

865
00:39:21,334 --> 00:39:24,751
start asking him questions
to answers we don't know."

866
00:39:24,834 --> 00:39:28,584
<i>So I had
this electronic organizer,</i>

867
00:39:28,667 --> 00:39:30,709
<i>the HP Jordana.</i>

868
00:39:30,792 --> 00:39:32,375
Soufan:
<i>Steve had downloaded</i>

869
00:39:32,459 --> 00:39:35,250
<i>the poster of
the 22 most-wanted terrorists</i>

870
00:39:35,334 --> 00:39:37,918
<i>that the FBI released
after 9/11.</i>

871
00:39:38,042 --> 00:39:39,751
<i>It had the people
who were involved</i>

872
00:39:39,834 --> 00:39:41,459
<i>in the East Africa
embassy bombings,</i>

873
00:39:41,542 --> 00:39:44,000
<i>the "USS Cole,"
and the Khobar bombing.</i>

874
00:39:44,083 --> 00:39:45,626
<i>All these individuals,</i>

875
00:39:45,709 --> 00:39:47,959
<i>from Mugniyah
to Bin Laden.</i>

876
00:39:48,042 --> 00:39:51,667
<i>So, Steve clicks a photo,
gives me the Palm Pilot.</i>

877
00:39:51,751 --> 00:39:54,792
I didn't look at it to check
if it's the right person,

878
00:39:54,876 --> 00:39:56,209
<i>but I showed Abu Zubaydah.</i>

879
00:39:56,292 --> 00:39:57,918
I said, "Is this the guy?"

880
00:39:58,000 --> 00:40:00,125
<i>And Abu Zubaydah said,</i>

881
00:40:00,209 --> 00:40:02,250
<i>"No, it's not."</i>

882
00:40:02,334 --> 00:40:05,250
I was convinced that al-Zayyat
is Abu Mohamed al-Masri,

883
00:40:05,334 --> 00:40:08,417
and I thought that
he's playing games.

884
00:40:08,500 --> 00:40:09,834
So I was really frustrated.

885
00:40:09,918 --> 00:40:12,250
I'm like, "Dude,
we saved your life.

886
00:40:12,334 --> 00:40:14,667
<i>"We're sitting here
like your next of kin,</i>

887
00:40:14,751 --> 00:40:16,250
<i>and you're still
playing games with us."</i>

888
00:40:16,334 --> 00:40:17,626
<i>And Abu Zubaydah
had enough of me.</i>

889
00:40:17,709 --> 00:40:19,876
He said, "Come on, brother,
I'm not playing games.

890
00:40:20,000 --> 00:40:21,167
You know who the guy is."

891
00:40:21,250 --> 00:40:23,500
I said,
"Who the fuck is he then?"

892
00:40:23,584 --> 00:40:27,209
And he said,
"Well, this is Mokhtar."

893
00:40:27,292 --> 00:40:31,584
<i>And when he said "Mokhtar,"
my heart stopped.</i>

894
00:40:31,667 --> 00:40:35,334
<i>Mokhtar, as Abu Zubaydah
identified from the picture,</i>

895
