01:10:11,792 --> 01:10:13,125
Lawyer:
Okay.

1557
01:10:14,876 --> 01:10:17,626
What did he have
tremendous expertise in?

1558
01:10:18,209 --> 01:10:20,209
In SERE.

1559
01:10:20,292 --> 01:10:22,542
Lawyer: What was his,
uh, SERE experience,

1560
01:10:22,626 --> 01:10:23,792
to your knowledge in,
at that time?

1561
01:10:23,876 --> 01:10:25,918
He had spent
many years, uh,

1562
01:10:26,000 --> 01:10:28,626
with the Air Force,
uh, working on SERE.

1563
01:10:28,709 --> 01:10:30,083
Lawyer: Okay.
Did he have...

1564
01:10:30,167 --> 01:10:33,709
was there any other source
of his tremendous expertise?

1565
01:10:33,792 --> 01:10:37,167
Uh, the expertise I was
interested in was SERE.

1566
01:10:42,042 --> 01:10:43,667
Mitchell:
<i>Once the CIA concluded</i>

1567
01:10:43,751 --> 01:10:46,083
<i>that he was
withholding information,</i>

1568
01:10:46,167 --> 01:10:49,209
<i>they pulled everybody back
in the early summer,</i>

1569
01:10:49,292 --> 01:10:51,083
<i>and it was clear to me</i>

1570
01:10:51,167 --> 01:10:53,292
<i>in the conversations that
were going around the table</i>

1571
01:10:53,375 --> 01:10:55,292
<i>that they had decided
they were going to use</i>

1572
01:10:55,375 --> 01:10:58,000
<i>physical coercion
against Abu Zubaydah.</i>

1573
01:10:58,083 --> 01:10:59,250
And I thought...

1574
01:11:00,375 --> 01:11:01,834
well, if you're gonna use it,

1575
01:11:01,918 --> 01:11:03,167
then you ought
to use something--

1576
01:11:03,250 --> 01:11:04,542
not that you should use it

1577
01:11:04,626 --> 01:11:06,167
or even that
it was desirable

1578
01:11:06,250 --> 01:11:07,542
or even that it was legal.

1579
01:11:07,626 --> 01:11:09,000
But if you're going
to do that,

1580
01:11:09,083 --> 01:11:10,626
then you ought to consider
using the things

1581
01:11:10,709 --> 01:11:12,334
that they've been using
at the SERE schools

1582
01:11:12,417 --> 01:11:14,626
because they don't produce
a lot of lasting injuries.

1583
01:11:14,709 --> 01:11:17,375
They don't produce injuries.

1584
01:11:17,459 --> 01:11:20,918
<i>So I gave them
a list of techniques
that they could consider.</i>

1585
01:11:26,292 --> 01:11:29,083
<i>Once they decided
they were going
to go forward with it,</i>

1586
01:11:29,167 --> 01:11:30,751
they began to, I guess...

1587
01:11:30,834 --> 01:11:32,250
I mean, we've got
all of the documents

1588
01:11:32,334 --> 01:11:35,042
released from the CIA,
so it's perfectly...

1589
01:11:35,125 --> 01:11:36,167
We can trace it,

1590
01:11:36,250 --> 01:11:38,042
you don't have to depend
on my memory.

1591
01:11:38,125 --> 01:11:40,167
Interviewer: I'm just
trying to reconcile too,

1592
01:11:40,250 --> 01:11:42,375
because we interviewed
James Mitchell,

1593
01:11:42,459 --> 01:11:45,375
and he puts the timeline
more towards June, July

1594
01:11:45,459 --> 01:11:47,500
that he proposes
the EIT program.

1595
01:11:47,584 --> 01:11:49,083
So, I'm just trying
to figure out, I'm just trying--

1596
01:11:49,167 --> 01:11:51,584
Well, that's not--
Yeah, that's not correct.

1597
01:11:51,667 --> 01:11:54,626
I mean, uh,
by June and July,

1598
01:11:54,709 --> 01:11:56,918
I was heavy
into discussions with the,

1599
01:11:57,000 --> 01:11:59,334
with the, uh,
Justice Department.

1600
01:11:59,417 --> 01:12:01,834
All I can tell you was

1601
01:12:01,918 --> 01:12:04,626
I was first told
about this idea

1602
01:12:04,709 --> 01:12:06,542
of Enhanced
Interrogation Techniques

1603
01:12:06,626 --> 01:12:10,459
in... sometime
in early to mid April.

1604
01:12:12,083 --> 01:12:14,334
Gibney:<i> When exactly were</i>
<i>the techniques invented?</i>

1605
01:12:14,417 --> 01:12:17,042
<i>The answer is the difference
between a wink and a nod</i>

1606
01:12:17,125 --> 01:12:18,584
<i>and a written plan.</i>

1607
01:12:18,667 --> 01:12:20,751
<i>In April and May,
Mitchell was experimenting</i>

1608
01:12:20,834 --> 01:12:23,000
<i>with SERE techniques
for which he had</i>

1609
01:12:23,083 --> 01:12:25,250
<i>no official legal approval.</i>

1610
01:12:25,334 --> 01:12:26,959
<i>To go further,
the techniques would have</i>

1611
01:12:27,042 --> 01:12:29,500
<i>to be codified
and approved in writing.</i>

1612
01:12:29,584 --> 01:12:32,042
Rizzo:<i> There was a team</i>
<i>that came up to my office</i>

1613
01:12:32,125 --> 01:12:34,042
one afternoon,
you know, unannounced.

1614
01:12:34,125 --> 01:12:35,709
I mean,
I had no preview.

1615
01:12:35,792 --> 01:12:39,042
I was just told it was
a matter of some urgency

1616
01:12:39,125 --> 01:12:42,209
about an operational proposal.
That's all I knew.

1617
01:12:42,292 --> 01:12:44,000
<i>And I was gobsmacked.</i>

1618
01:12:45,459 --> 01:12:48,292
My very first reaction was,
you guys are crazy.

1619
01:12:48,375 --> 01:12:49,918
This is, we shouldn't
be doing this.

1620
01:12:50,000 --> 01:12:52,709
We've never done
this kind of thing before.

1621
01:12:52,792 --> 01:12:55,751
<i>But I remember walking
around the CIA compound,</i>

1622
01:12:55,834 --> 01:12:58,042
<i>smoking a cigar,
trying to absorb</i>

1623
01:12:58,125 --> 01:12:59,375
<i>what I'd just been told.</i>

1624
01:12:59,459 --> 01:13:01,959
And I started to play out
the scenarios in my head,

1625
01:13:02,042 --> 01:13:03,209
that, okay,

1626
01:13:03,292 --> 01:13:04,667
<i>I go in to
the CIA director.</i>

1627
01:13:04,751 --> 01:13:06,417
<i>I say,
"We shouldn't do this.</i>

1628
01:13:06,500 --> 01:13:07,918
<i>"This is barbaric.</i>

1629
01:13:08,000 --> 01:13:10,167
<i>It may
or may not be legal."</i>

1630
01:13:10,250 --> 01:13:14,042
And on the other hand,
I thought, well, here
are all the experts.

1631
01:13:14,125 --> 01:13:18,000
Saying that, that these kinds
of aggressive measures

1632
01:13:18,083 --> 01:13:19,667
are the only ones

1633
01:13:19,751 --> 01:13:21,584
that we believe

1634
01:13:21,667 --> 01:13:23,876
will cause Abu Zubaydah

1635
01:13:23,959 --> 01:13:25,250
to tell us completely

1636
01:13:25,334 --> 01:13:27,584
what he knows about
another terrorist attack.

1637
01:13:29,500 --> 01:13:31,417
<i>And the idea
of the consequences</i>

1638
01:13:31,500 --> 01:13:34,751
<i>was something I couldn't
countenance on myself.</i>

1639
01:13:34,834 --> 01:13:36,542
<i>So that led
to a couple meetings</i>

1640
01:13:36,626 --> 01:13:37,834
<i>in George Tenet's office</i>

1641
01:13:37,918 --> 01:13:40,292
<i>with the senior
CIA leadership.</i>

1642
01:13:42,125 --> 01:13:45,667
Lawyer: So did you propose
any other list

1643
01:13:45,751 --> 01:13:47,083
other than this list

1644
01:13:47,167 --> 01:13:49,667
-to Mr. Rizzo
or to the department?
-No.

1645
01:13:49,751 --> 01:13:51,834
Lawyer: So you never proposed
any other list

1646
01:13:51,918 --> 01:13:53,584
-other than this list
to Mr. Rizzo?
-No.

1647
01:13:53,667 --> 01:13:55,500
Lawyer: Did you propose
any other list

1648
01:13:55,584 --> 01:13:57,709
other than this list
to the Department of Justice?

1649
01:13:57,792 --> 01:13:58,918
No.

1650
01:14:02,250 --> 01:14:04,042
Mitchell:<i> They began</i>
<i>to work back and forth</i>

1651
01:14:04,125 --> 01:14:06,459
with the Justice Department,
but they needed approval

1652
01:14:06,542 --> 01:14:08,083
<i>from Tenet to go forward.</i>

1653
01:14:08,167 --> 01:14:10,918
<i>And so I met
with Tenet, Rizzo.</i>

1654
01:14:11,000 --> 01:14:13,292
<i>Jose Rodriguez
took me up there,</i>

1655
01:14:13,375 --> 01:14:15,542
<i>and there were several
other people in the room.</i>

1656
01:14:15,626 --> 01:14:19,375
He asked me to describe
the techniques,
and I described them.

1657
01:14:19,459 --> 01:14:22,042
Rizzo:<i> They went through</i>
<i>each of these techniques.</i>

1658
01:14:22,125 --> 01:14:24,125
Mitchell:
<i>Attention grasps,</i>

1659
01:14:24,209 --> 01:14:25,125
<i>walling.</i>

1660
01:14:25,209 --> 01:14:28,042
Sort of a shock and awe
technique.

1661
01:14:28,125 --> 01:14:32,334
Mitchell:<i> Facial slaps,</i>
<i>a couple of stress positions...</i>

1662
01:14:32,417 --> 01:14:34,709
Rizzo:
<i>Extended sleep deprivation</i>

1663
01:14:34,792 --> 01:14:36,000
<i>for days.</i>

1664
01:14:36,083 --> 01:14:37,584
And the most
controversial one was,

1665
01:14:37,667 --> 01:14:39,626
of course, waterboarding.

1666
01:14:39,709 --> 01:14:41,626
Rizzo:<i> I'd never heard</i>
<i>of waterboarding.</i>

1667
01:14:41,709 --> 01:14:43,334
<i>I didn't even know
what the term meant.</i>

1668
01:14:43,417 --> 01:14:46,209
Simulated drowning is the way
it was described to me.

1669
01:14:49,626 --> 01:14:53,000
<i>And there was another one
that called for a mock burial.</i>

1670
01:14:53,083 --> 01:14:55,751
It sounded something
out of Edgar Allan Poe.

1671
01:14:55,834 --> 01:14:57,000
I think it was.

1672
01:14:58,584 --> 01:15:00,792
Mitchell:
<i>So Tenet gets up</i>
<i>to get a cigar.</i>

1673
01:15:00,876 --> 01:15:02,083
He didn't smoke
in the building,

1674
01:15:02,167 --> 01:15:04,375
but he had a cigar
quite frequently.

1675
01:15:05,292 --> 01:15:06,584
<i>He motions with his head</i>

1676
01:15:06,667 --> 01:15:08,876
<i>for Rizzo to walk
over there with him,</i>

1677
01:15:08,959 --> 01:15:11,417
<i>and he leans forward
and he says in a way</i>

1678
01:15:11,500 --> 01:15:13,500
<i>that I don't think
I'm supposed to hear.</i>

1679
01:15:13,584 --> 01:15:16,709
"Make sure this is legal
before we go forward
with this."

1680
01:15:18,250 --> 01:15:19,876
Rizzo:
<i>So that's when I decided</i>

1681
01:15:19,959 --> 01:15:22,334
<i>to seek
definitive legal guidance</i>

1682
01:15:22,417 --> 01:15:23,834
from the Department
of Justice

1683
01:15:23,918 --> 01:15:25,584
as to whether any or all

1684
01:15:25,667 --> 01:15:27,751
of these techniques
were legal

1685
01:15:27,834 --> 01:15:30,459
and if any crossed
the line into torture.

1686
01:15:31,834 --> 01:15:33,542
Gibney:<i> While the lawyers</i>
<i>in Washington worked</i>

1687
01:15:33,626 --> 01:15:36,042
<i>to make sure that
no one would be prosecuted</i>

1688
01:15:36,125 --> 01:15:38,584
<i>for using Mitchell's techniques
on Abu Zubaydah,</i>

1689
01:15:38,667 --> 01:15:42,834
<i>the prisoner himself
remained in Thailand, alone.</i>

1690
01:15:57,125 --> 01:16:00,125
(birds chirping)

1691
01:16:20,417 --> 01:16:23,626
Soufan:
<i>When all intelligence stopped</i>
<i>coming from Abu Zubaydah,</i>

1692
01:16:23,709 --> 01:16:26,083
<i>Mueller asked Tenet</i>

1693
01:16:26,167 --> 01:16:28,918
<i>why the intelligence stopped
from Abu Zubaydah,</i>

1694
01:16:29,000 --> 01:16:30,584
<i>what happened
with Abu Zubaydah.</i>

1695
01:16:32,000 --> 01:16:34,167
<i>And Tenet's response
to him was,</i>

1696
01:16:34,250 --> 01:16:36,667
<i>"Your guys
really messed him up.</i>

1697
01:16:36,751 --> 01:16:39,667
So we're, we're trying
to fix him."

1698
01:16:41,042 --> 01:16:45,000
<i>This was shocking to me,
because if you are trying</i>

1699
01:16:45,083 --> 01:16:48,459
<i>to get EITs approved,</i>

1700
01:16:48,542 --> 01:16:50,792
even though you were
doing it before,

1701
01:16:50,876 --> 01:16:53,918
if you're trying
to get EITs approved...

1702
01:16:55,459 --> 01:16:58,751
because of the
ticking bomb scenario, right,

1703
01:16:58,834 --> 01:17:03,292
<i>you don't leave a guy
with nobody interrogating him.</i>

1704
01:17:03,375 --> 01:17:05,876
Mitchell:<i> There's a difference</i>
<i>between a ticking time bomb</i>

1705
01:17:05,959 --> 01:17:08,292
<i>and a looming time bomb.</i>

1706
01:17:08,375 --> 01:17:10,792
At some point,
we realized

1707
01:17:10,876 --> 01:17:13,042
that it was
a looming time bomb,

1708
01:17:13,125 --> 01:17:14,542
not a ticking time bomb.

1709
01:17:14,626 --> 01:17:17,167
Uh, and, um...

1710
01:17:20,167 --> 01:17:22,375
So that's-- Of course,
we didn't know it at that time.

1711
01:17:22,459 --> 01:17:25,042
You'd have to ask the CIA
why they had that long.

1712
01:17:25,125 --> 01:17:26,792
I didn't, you know,
I wasn't in charge.

1713
01:17:26,876 --> 01:17:29,709
I didn't do it.
I'm not making light of it.
It was a long time.

1714
01:17:29,792 --> 01:17:31,250
Lawyer 2: Do you know
whether Abu Zubaydah

1715
01:17:31,334 --> 01:17:34,167
was asked any questions
during the isolation phase?

1716
01:17:35,083 --> 01:17:36,334
Did I know?

1717
01:17:36,417 --> 01:17:38,167
-Lawyer 2: Do you know now?
-Do I know now?

1718
01:17:38,250 --> 01:17:39,751
Uh, I've come--

1719
01:17:39,834 --> 01:17:41,959
yeah, I've come to learn that
there was a period of time

1720
01:17:42,042 --> 01:17:43,792
where he was
not asked questions.

1721
01:17:43,876 --> 01:17:46,459
Lawyer 2: And at the time,
did you know that?

1722
01:17:46,542 --> 01:17:48,667
At, at the very beginning,

1723
01:17:48,751 --> 01:17:51,042
as the techniques
were being described to me?

1724
01:17:51,125 --> 01:17:54,417
-At that point in time?
-Lawyer 2: At the time
when you were seeking

1725
01:17:54,500 --> 01:17:57,292
the Department
of Justice's opinion

1726
01:17:57,375 --> 01:17:58,626
on the techniques?

1727
01:17:58,709 --> 01:18:00,375
No, I don't believe so.

1728
01:18:11,417 --> 01:18:15,334
Jones:<i> The CIA is tasked</i>
<i>with stopping the next attack.</i>

1729
01:18:15,417 --> 01:18:18,042
Abu Zubaydah has been
providing intelligence

1730
01:18:18,125 --> 01:18:19,584
up until this point.

1731
01:18:19,667 --> 01:18:21,083
<i>And yet they leave him,</i>

1732
01:18:21,167 --> 01:18:23,709
<i>the only
high-value detainee,</i>

1733
01:18:23,792 --> 01:18:25,792
<i>alone without any contact.</i>

1734
01:18:27,542 --> 01:18:31,542
<i>During that period,
there are analysts still
sending in requirements.</i>

1735
01:18:31,626 --> 01:18:32,876
<i>One analyst says,</i>

1736
01:18:32,959 --> 01:18:34,959
"I want to learn more
about an individual

1737
01:18:35,042 --> 01:18:36,918
"who is in
Abu Zubaydah's address book.

1738
01:18:37,000 --> 01:18:39,792
<i>Abu Ahmed al-Kuwaiti."</i>

1739
01:18:39,876 --> 01:18:41,459
Of course,
nobody is around

1740
01:18:41,542 --> 01:18:43,292
to ask about
Abu Ahmed al-Kuwaiti.

1741
01:18:43,375 --> 01:18:44,292
(helicopter blades whirring)

1742
01:18:44,375 --> 01:18:46,125
(indistinct radio conversation)

1743
01:18:46,209 --> 01:18:47,751
<i>Nearly a decade later,</i>

1744
01:18:47,834 --> 01:18:50,459
<i>we finally obtained
Bin Laden's location,</i>

1745
01:18:50,542 --> 01:18:54,125
and it's through a man
named Abu Ahmed al-Kuwaiti.

1746
01:18:54,209 --> 01:18:55,959
So this lost opportunity

1747
01:18:56,042 --> 01:18:59,751
to ask Abu Zubaydah
in July of 2002,

1748
01:18:59,834 --> 01:19:02,667
when he's providing information
about a man in his address book

1749
01:19:02,751 --> 01:19:05,667
<i>who is Osama Bin Laden's
personal assistant</i>

1750
01:19:05,751 --> 01:19:08,125
<i>is a remarkable failure.</i>

1751
01:19:08,209 --> 01:19:11,626
Abu Zubaydah's isolation
was not about Abu Zubaydah.

1752
01:19:11,709 --> 01:19:15,000
It was about the politics
and legal opinions, right?

1753
01:19:15,083 --> 01:19:17,375
This was the idea
that we need to go hard.

1754
01:19:17,459 --> 01:19:20,000
We want it on paper that
you will not prosecute us

1755
01:19:20,083 --> 01:19:21,500
for engaging in torture.

1756
01:19:26,334 --> 01:19:28,751
<i>From the very beginning
in late 2001,</i>

1757
01:19:28,834 --> 01:19:30,417
<i>there were people
in the Agency,</i>

1758
01:19:30,500 --> 01:19:32,125
<i>in the
Counterterrorism Division,</i>

1759
01:19:32,209 --> 01:19:35,584
in their legal department
discussing torture.

1760
01:19:35,667 --> 01:19:37,042
<i>And they're using
the word "torture."</i>

1761
01:19:37,125 --> 01:19:39,083
<i>One email says
in the subject line,</i>

1762
01:19:39,167 --> 01:19:40,292
<i>"Torture update"</i>

1763
01:19:40,375 --> 01:19:42,417
And the lawyers,
not the operators,

1764
01:19:42,500 --> 01:19:44,125
not people who are
out in the field,

1765
01:19:44,209 --> 01:19:45,542
lawyers are discussing

1766
01:19:45,626 --> 01:19:48,167
how the CIA
can engage in torture

1767
01:19:48,250 --> 01:19:50,125
without being prosecuted
later on.

1768
01:19:50,209 --> 01:19:52,292
And in fact, they reach out
to the Department of Justice

1769
01:19:52,375 --> 01:19:55,083
to try to obtain
a declination of prosecution,

1770
01:19:55,167 --> 01:19:56,792
which says, "If we engage
in torture,

1771
01:19:56,876 --> 01:19:58,959
will you agree
not to prosecute us?"

1772
01:20:00,334 --> 01:20:03,292
Rizzo:
<i>After that initial</i>
<i>briefing by our people,</i>

1773
01:20:03,375 --> 01:20:06,751
<i>I convened a meeting
at the White House.</i>

1774
01:20:06,834 --> 01:20:10,459
<i>The initial reaction,
not just of the
Justice Department lawyers,</i>

1775
01:20:10,542 --> 01:20:11,876
but the White House counsel,

1776
01:20:11,959 --> 01:20:13,918
and the National Security
Council legal advisors

1777
01:20:14,000 --> 01:20:17,292
was what
my initial reaction was.

1778
01:20:17,375 --> 01:20:19,375
What, what is this stuff,
I mean, you know,

1779
01:20:19,459 --> 01:20:21,042
it was just
so beyond anything

