01:48:54,667 --> 01:48:56,834
to let the facts take us
where they will.

2456
01:48:56,918 --> 01:48:58,125
Michael Hayden testifies

2457
01:48:58,209 --> 01:49:00,209
that this was not
destruction of evidence.

2458
01:49:00,292 --> 01:49:02,042
In fact, the CIA has

2459
01:49:02,125 --> 01:49:03,918
very detailed
written records

2460
01:49:04,000 --> 01:49:06,334
of everything that happened
at the detention site,

2461
01:49:06,417 --> 01:49:08,209
so it didn't need
those videotapes.

2462
01:49:08,292 --> 01:49:09,918
There are written records.

2463
01:49:10,000 --> 01:49:11,959
And he says if the committee
wants to see those records,

2464
01:49:12,042 --> 01:49:13,626
of course it can see
those records.

2465
01:49:13,709 --> 01:49:15,792
So what does the committee
say immediately?

2466
01:49:15,876 --> 01:49:17,834
"We want to see
these records tomorrow."

2467
01:49:18,876 --> 01:49:20,542
<i>The committee finally acquires</i>

2468
01:49:20,626 --> 01:49:22,709
<i>those heavily redacted cables</i>

2469
01:49:22,792 --> 01:49:24,959
<i>in May of 2008,</i>

2470
01:49:25,042 --> 01:49:27,417
<i>and myself and two other
Senate staffers</i>

2471
01:49:27,500 --> 01:49:28,626
<i>are sent to the CIA</i>

2472
01:49:28,709 --> 01:49:31,334
<i>to review these cables
and write a report.</i>

2473
01:49:32,459 --> 01:49:33,751
<i>The CIA eventually gave us</i>

2474
01:49:33,834 --> 01:49:37,167
<i>6.3 million pages
of documents.</i>

2475
01:49:37,250 --> 01:49:40,959
We identified at least
119 CIA detainees.

2476
01:49:41,042 --> 01:49:43,375
Reporter:<i> But at the heart</i>
<i>of this release today</i>

2477
01:49:43,459 --> 01:49:45,834
<i>is the conclusion
that the interrogations</i>

2478
01:49:45,918 --> 01:49:48,334
<i>did not make
the country safer</i>

2479
01:49:48,417 --> 01:49:50,459
<i>and that
the CIA misled</i>

2480
01:49:50,542 --> 01:49:52,584
<i>the Bush administration
about the program.</i>

2481
01:49:52,667 --> 01:49:54,500
Jones:
<i>We saw constant manipulation</i>

2482
01:49:54,584 --> 01:49:56,417
<i>of the White House,
the Department of Justice,</i>

2483
01:49:56,500 --> 01:49:57,667
<i>and Congress by the CIA.</i>

2484
01:49:57,751 --> 01:49:59,250
I mean, this is what
I thought would be

2485
01:49:59,334 --> 01:50:00,584
the most important finding

2486
01:50:00,667 --> 01:50:03,167
coming out of the Senate
Intelligence Committee report.

2487
01:50:03,250 --> 01:50:05,876
<i>You know, misleading Bush,
misleading Obama,</i>

2488
01:50:05,959 --> 01:50:08,876
<i>misleading the Congress,
repeatedly we see this.</i>

2489
01:50:08,959 --> 01:50:11,500
<i>John Brennan,
CIA director under Obama,</i>

2490
01:50:11,584 --> 01:50:13,417
<i>made a speech
after the report came out</i>

2491
01:50:13,500 --> 01:50:15,000
<i>and said we'll never know</i>

2492
01:50:15,083 --> 01:50:17,584
<i>if we could've gotten
this intelligence
in any other way.</i>

2493
01:50:17,667 --> 01:50:20,250
<i>...and the ultimate provision
of the information</i>

2494
01:50:20,334 --> 01:50:22,626
<i>is unknown and unknowable.</i>

2495
01:50:22,709 --> 01:50:25,292
Jones:<i> But we do know,</i>
<i>we have an entire report,</i>

2496
01:50:25,375 --> 01:50:28,125
500 pages here
with almost 3,000 footnotes

2497
01:50:28,209 --> 01:50:30,292
and a 7,000-page
classified report

2498
01:50:30,375 --> 01:50:31,709
with 38,000 footnotes

2499
01:50:31,792 --> 01:50:33,667
<i>that says
we do know that, in fact,</i>

2500
01:50:33,751 --> 01:50:35,042
<i>the capture of Jose Padilla</i>

2501
01:50:35,125 --> 01:50:36,667
<i>did not come
from the waterboarding</i>

2502
01:50:36,751 --> 01:50:37,959
<i>of Abu Zubaydah.</i>

2503
01:50:38,042 --> 01:50:40,209
We do know that,
because the records
are there.

2504
01:50:40,292 --> 01:50:42,167
<i>We tortured some folks.</i>

2505
01:50:42,250 --> 01:50:44,959
<i>We did some things that were
contrary to our values.</i>

2506
01:50:45,042 --> 01:50:47,042
<i>It's important for us</i>

2507
01:50:47,125 --> 01:50:48,959
<i>not to,</i>

2508
01:50:49,042 --> 01:50:52,292
<i>uh, feel too sanctimonious</i>

2509
01:50:52,375 --> 01:50:53,876
<i>in retrospect</i>

2510
01:50:53,959 --> 01:50:56,083
<i>about the tough job
that those folks have.</i>

2511
01:50:56,167 --> 01:50:58,000
<i>And a lot of those folks</i>

2512
01:50:58,083 --> 01:51:00,626
were working hard,

2513
01:51:00,709 --> 01:51:04,834
under enormous pressure,
and are real patriots.

2514
01:51:04,918 --> 01:51:07,209
But having said all that...

2515
01:51:07,292 --> 01:51:10,417
we did some things
that were wrong.

2516
01:51:10,500 --> 01:51:12,667
Jones:<i> I remember hearing</i>
<i>that line about patriots</i>

2517
01:51:12,751 --> 01:51:14,375
<i>and thinking
about the people</i>

2518
01:51:14,459 --> 01:51:16,167
<i>who said they were resigning
from the CIA,</i>

2519
01:51:16,250 --> 01:51:18,292
<i>people who said they didn't
want to be involved
in this program</i>

2520
01:51:18,375 --> 01:51:21,042
and the people who engaged
in the torture,

2521
01:51:21,125 --> 01:51:22,292
who defended the torture.

2522
01:51:22,375 --> 01:51:26,542
And this is who Obama identifies
as real patriots.

2523
01:51:26,626 --> 01:51:29,042
Gibney:<i> The word "patriot"</i>
<i>struck a chord with me.</i>

2524
01:51:29,125 --> 01:51:31,500
<i>So long as you believe
you're a patriot,</i>

2525
01:51:31,584 --> 01:51:33,834
<i>do the ends
always justify the means?</i>

2526
01:51:33,918 --> 01:51:35,876
<i>And if we all believe that,</i>

2527
01:51:35,959 --> 01:51:38,417
<i>are we prepared
to abandon our principles</i>

2528
01:51:38,500 --> 01:51:39,959
<i>in order to defend them?</i>

2529
01:51:42,709 --> 01:51:44,542
<i>Jose Rodriguez
and James Mitchell</i>

2530
01:51:44,626 --> 01:51:45,876
<i>both live in Florida.</i>

2531
01:51:45,959 --> 01:51:48,334
<i>Mitchell's company
grossed $81 million</i>

2532
01:51:48,417 --> 01:51:50,125
<i>for his interrogation services.</i>

2533
01:51:50,209 --> 01:51:52,959
<i>Rodriguez became
an intelligence consultant</i>

2534
01:51:53,042 --> 01:51:54,626
<i>working for IBM.</i>

2535
01:51:54,709 --> 01:51:56,751
<i>He has a fondness for
Corvettes and Harleys</i>

2536
01:51:56,834 --> 01:51:58,792
<i>and owns
a 30-foot powerboat</i>

2537
01:51:58,876 --> 01:52:01,375
<i>called "Shaken, Not Stirred."</i>

2538
01:52:01,459 --> 01:52:02,792
<i>It's a great thing
about this government,</i>

2539
01:52:02,876 --> 01:52:04,250
<i>the only people
that ever stand up</i>

2540
01:52:04,334 --> 01:52:06,626
<i>and tell the truth are who,
intelligence officers,</i>

2541
01:52:06,709 --> 01:52:08,876
<i>because our culture is never
break faith with the truth.</i>

2542
01:52:08,959 --> 01:52:11,500
<i>We'll tell you, you don't have
to drag it out of us.</i>

2543
01:52:21,500 --> 01:52:22,918
Mitchell:<i> You're not</i>
<i>going to get me</i>

2544
01:52:23,000 --> 01:52:24,292
<i>to say I think
it's torture.</i>

2545
01:52:24,375 --> 01:52:25,918
<i>You might as well
just quit.</i>

2546
01:52:26,000 --> 01:52:28,334
If you want to think
it's torture, think
what you want to think.

2547
01:52:28,417 --> 01:52:30,584
I'm not in the business
of controlling your mind,

2548
01:52:30,667 --> 01:52:32,667
nor am I in the business
of trying to coerce you

2549
01:52:32,751 --> 01:52:34,584
into saying something
that you don't believe

2550
01:52:34,667 --> 01:52:36,876
or want to comment on.

2551
01:52:37,000 --> 01:52:40,042
<i>This was the least worse
of two bad choices.</i>

2552
01:52:40,125 --> 01:52:41,751
<i>Both choices suck.</i>

2553
01:52:41,834 --> 01:52:43,876
<i>Both choices are bad.</i>

2554
01:52:43,959 --> 01:52:45,667
<i>But on the one hand,
you have</i>

2555
01:52:45,751 --> 01:52:47,292
<i>thousands of dead Americans</i>

2556
01:52:47,375 --> 01:52:48,667
<i>and on the other hand,
you have</i>

2557
01:52:48,751 --> 01:52:50,834
<i>the temporary discomfort
of a terrorist.</i>

2558
01:52:52,375 --> 01:52:55,167
<i>I thought there was going to be
a major catastrophic attack</i>

2559
01:52:55,250 --> 01:52:57,959
<i>that was going to kill
millions of Americans.</i>

2560
01:52:58,042 --> 01:52:59,250
And, uh...

2561
01:53:04,417 --> 01:53:07,459
I thought that
my government had asked me

2562
01:53:07,542 --> 01:53:09,751
to stop it.

2563
01:53:09,834 --> 01:53:13,125
And I felt responsible...
for doing that.

2564
01:53:13,209 --> 01:53:14,709
That's what I thought.

2565
01:53:20,876 --> 01:53:22,375
Gibney:<i> From near</i>
<i>his home in Florida,</i>

2566
01:53:22,459 --> 01:53:24,918
<i>Mitchell can paddle
to the Gulf of Mexico.</i>

2567
01:53:26,250 --> 01:53:27,542
<i>From there,
it's a straight shot</i>

2568
01:53:27,626 --> 01:53:29,626
<i>to Cuba
and Guantanamo,</i>

2569
01:53:29,709 --> 01:53:32,334
<i>where Abu Zubaydah
lives out his days.</i>

2570
01:53:32,417 --> 01:53:34,000
<i>As its creators intended,</i>

2571
01:53:34,083 --> 01:53:36,459
<i>Gitmo is a kind of
nowhere land</i>

2572
01:53:36,542 --> 01:53:38,709
<i>outside of time and place.</i>

2573
01:53:38,792 --> 01:53:42,167
<i>The images you see here
were shot by me in 2006.</i>

2574
01:53:42,250 --> 01:53:44,292
<i>The government
won't permit me to return,</i>

2575
01:53:44,375 --> 01:53:46,459
<i>so I depend on others
to tell me</i>

2576
01:53:46,542 --> 01:53:47,876
<i>not much has changed.</i>

2577
01:53:47,959 --> 01:53:51,334
<i>Fast food,
first-run movies,</i>

2578
01:53:51,417 --> 01:53:53,500
<i>the gift shop
where I bought my T-shirt,</i>

2579
01:53:53,584 --> 01:53:57,459
<i>sporting a local joke
about interrogators.</i>

2580
01:53:57,542 --> 01:53:59,834
<i>After Thailand,
Abu Zubaydah would be sent</i>

2581
01:53:59,918 --> 01:54:01,417
<i>to black sites
in Poland,</i>

2582
01:54:01,500 --> 01:54:03,292
<i>Lithuania, and Morocco.</i>

2583
01:54:03,375 --> 01:54:05,334
<i>When he first landed
in Gitmo,</i>

2584
01:54:05,417 --> 01:54:08,083
<i>he was imprisoned
in the secret CIA unit</i>

2585
01:54:08,167 --> 01:54:10,334
<i>known as Strawberry Fields,</i>

2586
01:54:10,417 --> 01:54:11,918
<i>as in forever.</i>

2587
01:54:12,000 --> 01:54:15,042
<i>♪ Strawberry fields forever ♪</i>

2588
01:54:15,125 --> 01:54:17,250
<i>Recently, along with
the 13 others</i>

2589
01:54:17,334 --> 01:54:19,500
<i>held in indefinite detention,</i>

2590
01:54:19,584 --> 01:54:23,209
<i>he was moved to
Guantanamo's Camp V.</i>

2591
01:54:23,292 --> 01:54:26,375
<i>No one will say what kind
of law governs Abu Zubaydah.</i>

2592
01:54:26,459 --> 01:54:28,167
<i>So he has two legal teams,</i>

2593
01:54:28,250 --> 01:54:31,459
<i>one civilian and one
for the military commissions.</i>

2594
01:54:31,542 --> 01:54:33,751
<i>His military lawyer,
Chantell Higgins,</i>

2595
01:54:33,834 --> 01:54:35,167
<i>sees him most often.</i>

2596
01:54:37,000 --> 01:54:39,500
Zayn is
a colorful storyteller.

2597
01:54:40,292 --> 01:54:41,334
<i>Very funny.</i>

2598
01:54:41,417 --> 01:54:43,918
<i>Always well-dressed.
Very particular.</i>

2599
01:54:44,000 --> 01:54:47,792
<i>He's a sort of a...</i>

2600
01:54:47,876 --> 01:54:50,626
how do I say it, a diva.
(laughs)

2601
01:54:53,209 --> 01:54:55,959
Gibney:<i> Does he suffer</i>
<i>from some kind of PTSD?</i>

2602
01:54:56,042 --> 01:54:58,125
I don't know how anyone
could have endured that

2603
01:54:58,209 --> 01:55:00,584
and not suffered
from PTSD.

2604
01:55:00,667 --> 01:55:03,125
I know that he has nightmares
about drowning.

2605
01:55:04,167 --> 01:55:05,751
<i>Waking up and drowning.</i>

2606
01:55:16,959 --> 01:55:18,918
Gibney:<i> To what extent</i>
<i>does Abu Zubaydah remember</i>

2607
01:55:19,000 --> 01:55:20,751
anything about James Mitchell?

2608
01:55:20,834 --> 01:55:22,834
Does he remember
who he was?

2609
01:55:22,918 --> 01:55:24,250
(sighs)

2610
01:55:25,918 --> 01:55:29,125
Uh, yeah, he remembers
very clearly who he was.

2611
01:55:30,584 --> 01:55:31,751
Yeah.

2612
01:55:31,834 --> 01:55:34,209
Gibney:
And does he understand
that he was the guy

2613
01:55:34,292 --> 01:55:36,042
who designed
these techniques?

2614
01:55:36,125 --> 01:55:37,250
He does.

2615
01:55:37,334 --> 01:55:39,792
I think all the detainees
understand that by now.

2616
01:55:42,125 --> 01:55:45,542
Rizzo:<i> Abu Zubaydah was</i>
<i>the first high-level detainee.</i>

2617
01:55:45,626 --> 01:55:47,125
<i>But he's not
one of the ones</i>

2618
01:55:47,209 --> 01:55:50,542
who have actually been charged
by the military commissions.

2619
01:55:50,626 --> 01:55:54,959
So his status is...
really permanent limbo.

2620
01:55:55,042 --> 01:55:56,709
I can't imagine
any US President

2621
01:55:56,792 --> 01:55:59,250
in any US administration
ever letting him go.

2622
01:55:59,334 --> 01:56:02,334
But what do you do
with him?

2623
01:56:02,417 --> 01:56:04,167
Lt. Col. Chantell Higgins:
<i>In America,</i>
<i>we have this thing</i>

2624
01:56:04,250 --> 01:56:06,292
<i>called innocent
until proven guilty.</i>

2625
01:56:06,375 --> 01:56:08,250
<i>If we think they're
guilty of something</i>

2626
01:56:08,334 --> 01:56:10,250
<i>we should take them
to trial,</i>

2627
01:56:10,334 --> 01:56:12,876
<i>give them opportunity
to be heard,</i>

2628
01:56:12,959 --> 01:56:16,167
<i>sentence them accordingly,
and send them on their way.</i>

2629
01:56:17,542 --> 01:56:20,709
It's just inhumane

2630
01:56:20,792 --> 01:56:24,125
to... detain someone...

2631
01:56:24,959 --> 01:56:27,209
and not give them rights.

2632
01:56:27,876 --> 01:56:28,876
Period.

2633
01:56:31,083 --> 01:56:32,667
Mora:<i> Almost half</i>
<i>of the American public believes</i>

2634
01:56:32,751 --> 01:56:35,042
<i>that the use of torture
is acceptable.</i>

2635
01:56:35,125 --> 01:56:37,709
<i>There's growing acceptance
of the use of cruelty</i>

2636
01:56:37,792 --> 01:56:39,000
<i>as a tool</i>

2637
01:56:39,083 --> 01:56:41,500
to address
social situations

2638
01:56:41,584 --> 01:56:43,667
or national security crises.

2639
01:56:43,751 --> 01:56:45,542
And I think in the right
combination of situations,

2640
01:56:45,626 --> 01:56:48,834
you have other individuals
who'll say,

2641
01:56:48,918 --> 01:56:51,250
"This is another tool
we should use again,"

2642
01:56:51,334 --> 01:56:53,667
and we'll go back to use it
despite all the reasons

2643
01:56:53,751 --> 01:56:56,042
why it shouldn't be
countenanced again.

2644
01:56:59,667 --> 01:57:01,334
Gibney:
<i>For nearly 20 years,</i>

2645
01:57:01,417 --> 01:57:04,042
<i>Abu Zubaydah has been
in US custody.</i>

2646
01:57:04,125 --> 01:57:06,375
<i>In all that time,
the man with one eye</i>

2647
01:57:06,459 --> 01:57:07,751
<i>and one good leg</i>

2648
01:57:07,834 --> 01:57:11,626
<i>has remained
mostly incommunicado.</i>

2649
01:57:11,709 --> 01:57:13,626
<i>I can see some
of his drawings.</i>

2650
01:57:13,709 --> 01:57:15,459
<i>I can read censored letters,</i>

2651
01:57:15,542 --> 01:57:17,542
<i>and the briefs
of his lawyers.</i>

2652
01:57:17,626 --> 01:57:19,375
<i>But I cannot talk to him.</i>

2653
01:57:19,459 --> 01:57:21,000
<i>His voice has been kept silent,</i>

2654
01:57:21,083 --> 01:57:23,250
<i>just as the CIA promised.</i>

2655
01:57:24,417 --> 01:57:26,125
<i>He's the forever prisoner</i>

2656
01:57:26,209 --> 01:57:27,709
<i>meant to fade from memory</i>

2657
01:57:27,792 --> 01:57:30,542
<i>like old photographs
left in the sun.</i>

2658
01:57:42,042 --> 01:57:43,792
<i>Twenty years after 9/11,</i>

2659
01:57:43,876 --> 01:57:45,542
<i>I'm stirred to remember
the innocents</i>

2660
01:57:45,626 --> 01:57:47,792
<i>who died on that day.</i>

2661
01:57:47,876 --> 01:57:50,000
<i>But I'm also stirred
to remember the purpose</i>

2662
01:57:50,083 --> 01:57:52,209
<i>of that vicious attack.</i>

2663
01:57:52,292 --> 01:57:53,792
<i>It wasn't to win a war.</i>

2664
01:57:53,876 --> 01:57:55,417
<i>It was to provoke us
to abandon</i>

2665
01:57:55,500 --> 01:57:59,250
<i>the principles of democracy
we claim to live by.</i>

2666
01:57:59,334 --> 01:58:01,626
<i>The forever prisoner
is a living reminder</i>

2667
01:58:01,709 --> 01:58:03,876
<i>of one of the ideals
we abandoned:</i>

2668
01:58:03,959 --> 01:58:06,167
<i>equal justice
under the law.</i>

2669
01:58:06,250 --> 01:58:07,709
<i>As the saying goes,</i>

2670
01:58:07,792 --> 01:58:10,500
<i>there is no them,
there is only us.</i>

2671
01:58:11,500 --> 01:58:13,167
<i>If we believe in that idea,</i>

2672
01:58:13,250 --> 01:58:15,959
<i>how can we imprison a man
without charge</i>

2673
01:58:16,042 --> 01:58:18,167
<i>for the remainder of his life?</i>

2674
01:58:18,250 --> 01:58:20,209
<i>Not for what he did to us...</i>

2675
01:58:20,292 --> 01:58:22,667
<i>but for what
we did to him.</i>

2676
01:58:23,751 --> 01:58:26,626
